post_text:
As we move into Fall, we are already seeing quite a few cases of Strep going around. Just as a reminder, below is the picture that was also sent home in parent packets. If your child spikes a fever above 100.4, please take your child in to be tested, and if they have something other than COVID, they can come back to school if we receive a medical letter stating so. It does not need to state what they do have, just that they do not have COVID.

If you are watching the numbers in the county, we do have an increase in both exposure and positive cases within the communities. So far, we have not been notified of anything within the school, but if we are, we will send home a letter and do a school reach notifying parents. Again, it will be a general letter without names just notifying parents.

Thank you for your continued diligence in keeping everyone safe and in school! We are already toward the end of our second full week!!!

post_text: The typical open house will not be held this year, but you will be able to set up a time with teachers by going to the webpage and signing up under your child's (ren's) grade level to meet the teacher, drop off supplies, and see your classroom from 5-7PM on the 13th. This is by no means a requirement, just an option. There will be no booths, no food this year, just whether or not you want time with your teacher prior to the beginning of the year. We know this time can be pretty important to the younger kids especially that may have nerves about beginning the year, especially when learning from home for so long. Thank you for your flexibility! Hopefully we will all be able to get back to normal operation sooner than later!

Just to clarify: Armour School District is NOT mandating masks for students in the Fall. This action has been passed by the school board. If you want your child to wear a mask, they are welcome to, but we will not mandate it during the day.
Also, if you would like your child to be served by the district, but have concerns about sending them, please let us know. We have the option of kids participating distance while still working with their classmates through live classes. The students will log in during normal class periods and our teachers will teach distance and in-person students as one.

post_text:
FALL PLANS.
Armour School District is dedicated to returning in the fall in person for all classes. Currently, we are adjusting many things within our facility to ensure social distancing and grade isolation to foster health and well-being in the fall. As we transition into a new normal, please note that if anyone in your household tests positive for COVID-19, your children will be quarantined for the 14 day advised time frame during which the school will provide learning via distance education. In this light, please let us know if you have no internet, or if you would need an additional hot spot to help support the amount of learners in your household so that we can prepare appropriately. If you would text 605-572-0002 with your family name and request(additional hot spot, or internet needed) that will help us ensure our budget matches needs appropriately. Please do so by Friday, July 3rd. If you need no additional support, you do not need to text. Thank you for your diligence to helping us all succeed during this pandemic.

post_text:
Happy Friday to you all! Some information on what we have learned in this last week. As many of you have already heard, the Governor has asked for schools to stay out of the building for the rest of the school year. Although we will not be together in building, we will continue our flexible learning platform through the original school calendar.

Also, teachers are working on cleaning out desks and lockers. We are securing all items into bags that will be sent home with assignments on the Friday after Easter (4/17).

We continue to work on a re-entry plan for the Fall. We are asking for a potential approval of a post-Labor Day beginning to the school year should we need it, but our already approved calendar for next year will be our default primary schedule. We are planning for what could be seen as "worst case scenario" and hoping not to need it.

Thank you for your continued support for our staff and our school district! Thank you for all that you continue to champion at home for your families and children! Please call or text with any questions: 605-572-0002

post_text: The reason we have a separate drop off and pick up day is because once the packets are returned, they go directly into loaded totes and sit for 48 hours prior to any exposure to anyone else. When returned on Friday, they can sit all weekend in the totes without disturbance, and then can still be graded the following week. If they come back on Mondays, which would be less work for school staff as well, they must sit until midday Wednesday before anything can be touched and feedback to students will be that much more delayed. The teachers are already accounting the half day Monday and half day Friday into the work they are giving out as being lighter days.

CORONAVIRUS INFORMATION.
You will find a letter from the school district coming home with your child(ren) tonight. Please read it. We highlight both what the school is doing to take precautionary steps, but also what you can do to protect yourselves at home. Essentially, the care taken is to wash your hands thoroughly, for 20 second with soap before rinsing, and to wash often. In addition, wipe down any surface areas that have high hand traffic with wipes. The CDC put out that 5Tbsp. of bleach diluted to a gallon of water would work well to spray and let dry. We will also be using our school social media platforms to provide more community health awareness and tips and tricks to staying healthy that the CDC has suggested. Thank you! Andrea

As we work to ensure our students and families are safe, we share this comic developed just for kids. At times we may think that their ears are unaware, but they hear our conversations and can become scared. We are sharing this comic that promotes healthy hygiene and provides guidance for what kids can do to help with our staff and students, as well as with our families. Copies will come home with your children so that you too can help provide guidance and calm any fears for your family.

post_text:
Hi All,
I have attached a graphic of the survey responses that have been received online at this point in time. We have additionally received paper copy surveys that will be tabulated and shared out either this afternoon or evening.

Please keep in mind that the survey was NOT an official vote to build, it was simply a "temperature check" on starting the conversation on facility planning. That is why there was not more shared prior to the meeting (although present in our board minutes since last year March), we had no solid information on what costs would be based on building needs to share.

Armour School District's responsibility is to educate and give options. The final decision, if and when it is appropriate to be addressed, happens in an official community vote that requires a 60% super majority.

Thank you

post_text: I was asked specifically about Brosz Engineering's involvement in the development of a plan based on Clint being employed by Brosz Engineering. The only thing that Brosz did, which was done by Clint, was the site eval. This was done for free. The engineering part is a bid process, Angie at ID8 holds those contracts. I did file this last meeting for a conflict of interest with the board even though no money was involved to ensure that people knew he was involved with part of it. That is also why the Brosz name was not removed from the pamphlets- transparency is really important, especially when talking about tax payer dollars. If there are any more questions, please feel free to ask. I am putting together information that will also be put in the newspaper with some of the feedback given.
